  "prompt": "What function do we use in Java in place of cin>> in C++?",
  "response": "In Java, instead of using `cin>>` from C++, you typically use different methods for input depending on the type of input and the source:\n\n1. For console input (similar to `cin>>` for reading from standard input):\n   ```java\n   import java.util.Scanner;\n\n   Scanner scanner = new Scanner(System.in);\n\n   // Reading different types of input\n   int number = scanner.nextInt();        // Read an integer\n   double decimal = scanner.nextDouble(); // Read a double\n   String text = scanner.next();          // Read a word\n   String wholeLine = scanner.nextLine(); // Read a whole line\n   ```\n\n2. For primitive types, you can also use:\n   ```java\n   import java.io.BufferedReader;\n   import java.io.InputStreamReader;\n\n   BufferedReader reader = new BufferedReader(new InputStreamReader(System.in));\n   String input = reader.readLine(); // Read a line as a string\n   ```\n\nThe `Scanner` class is more commonly used and provides more flexible input parsing compared to `BufferedReader`.\n\nExample usage:\n```java\nimport java.util.Scanner;\n\npublic class InputExample {\n    public static void main(String[] args) {\n        Scanner scanner = new Scanner(System.in);\n        \n        System.out.print(\"Enter an integer: \");\n        int num = scanner.nextInt();\n        \n        System.out.print(\"Enter a string: \");\n        String str = scanner.next();\n        \n        System.out.println(\"You entered: \" + num + \" and \" + str);\n        \n        scanner.close(); // Good practice to close the scanner when done\n    }\n}\n```\n\nKey differences from C++:\n- Use `Scanner` instead of `cin`\n- Methods like `nextInt()`, `nextDouble()`, `next()`, `nextLine()`\n- Require importing `java.util.Scanner`\n- Need to close the scanner with `scanner.close()`",
